## 8. Request flow — end to end

```
 1. Client sends HTTPS request to <public-ip>:443, Host: app.test.com
        │
        ▼
 2. CloudStack Firewall rule
        - Allows inbound TCP/443 to reach the network
        ▼
 3. CloudStack Load Balancer rule
        - Distributes traffic across worker node IPs
        - Forwards to: <worker-node-ip>:31187 (NodePort)
        ▼
 4. kube-proxy (on the receiving node)
        - NodePort 31187 is opened on every node by kube-proxy, regardless
          of which node the Ingress controller pod actually runs on
        - iptables/IPVS rules forward the packet to a live HAProxy
          controller pod IP (possibly on a different node)
        ▼
 5. HAProxy Ingress Controller pod
        - Terminates TLS using the cert from the `web-app-tls` Secret
        - Reads the `Ingress` object (`web-app-ingress`) to match the
          Host header (`app.test.com`) to a backend Service
        - Forwards the decrypted request internally as plain HTTP
        ▼
 6. Service `web-app-svc` (ClusterIP)
        - A virtual IP; kube-proxy uses its Endpoints/EndpointSlice to
          pick one of the live nginx pod IPs
        ▼
 7. nginx pod (one of 3 replicas)
        - Serves the response on containerPort 8080
        ▼
 8. Response travels back up the same path in reverse
```
### Full flow path ###
1. Browser/client
       │  HTTPS request to 103.232.25.196:443, Host: app.test.com
       ▼
2. CloudStack Public IP (103.232.25.196)
       │  Firewall rule: allow inbound TCP/443
       │  Load Balancer rule: public 443 → NodePort 31187, across both worker VMs
       ▼
3. CloudStack Load Balancer (virtual router / LB appliance)
       │  Picks one of the two worker nodes (round robin), forwards to:
       │  10.1.1.85:31187  or  10.1.1.135:31187
       ▼
4. Worker Node — kube-proxy / iptables (or IPVS) rules
       │  NodePort 31187 is opened on EVERY node by kube-proxy, regardless of
       │  which node actually runs the HAProxy pod. kube-proxy's iptables/IPVS
       │  rules intercept traffic hitting 31187 and forward it to one of the
       │  HAProxy controller pod's actual IPs (even if that pod is running on
       │  the OTHER node) — this is why NodePort works cluster-wide, not just
       │  on the node where the pod happens to live.
       ▼
5. HAProxy Ingress controller pod (namespace: haproxy-controller)
       │  - Terminates TLS here (decrypts HTTPS) using the cert from the
       │    'web-app-tls' Secret (or its fallback self-signed cert, in your
       │    case, until you create that Secret)
       │  - Reads the Ingress object 'web-app-ingress' to know:
       │      Host: app.test.com  →  route to Service 'web-app-svc' on port 80
       │  - Forwards the now-decrypted request as plain HTTP internally
       ▼
6. Kubernetes Service — web-app-svc (ClusterIP 10.110.40.233)
       │  Doesn't do the routing itself — it's a virtual IP. The actual
       │  forwarding to real pod IPs is done by kube-proxy again, using the
       │  Service's Endpoints/EndpointSlice object, which lists the live
       │  pod IPs backing the 'app=web-app' selector.
       ▼
7. One of the 3 web-app pods (chosen via the Service's load balancing)
       │  nginx listens on containerPort 8080, serves the request
       ▼
8. Response travels back up the exact same path in reverse

### Component responsibilities at a glance

| Layer | Component | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Network edge | CloudStack Firewall rule | Allow/deny inbound traffic by port/protocol/CIDR |
| Network edge | CloudStack Load Balancer rule | Distribute public traffic across worker node IPs |
| Node | kube-proxy | Implements NodePort routing and Service load balancing via iptables/IPVS |
| Cluster | HAProxy Ingress Controller | TLS termination, Host/path-based routing, reads `Ingress` objects |
| Cluster | `Ingress` object | Declarative routing rules (no traffic handling itself) |
| Cluster | `Service` (ClusterIP) | Stable virtual IP fronting a set of pods |
| Cluster | `Endpoints`/`EndpointSlice` | Live list of pod IPs backing a Service |
| Application | nginx pods | Serve the actual HTTP response |

